"that debt in the Corporation or, where, after the making of the order, the rights of those persons in respect of those shares or that subordinated debt have been assigned to or have devolved on other persons, those other persons.";
(g) by striking out line 9 on page 16 and substituting the following:
"that debt in the Corporation or, where, after the making of the order, the rights of those persons in respect of those shares or that subordinated debt have been assigned to or have devolved on other persons, those other persons."
He said: Mr. Speaker, this motion is pursuant to the Senate discussions on this bill. It makes it easier for holders of shares and subordinated debt of a vested company to sell the rights to compensation attached to those shares to others.
What happens is we FIRP the company and then there is some time before the shares are either bought out by the CDIC or whether they are given back to the company that is FIRPed.
In the meantime these particular assets might be sold and this amendment provides for a sale of these assets in that intervening period. The amendments do this by permitting the CDIC to hand over shares and debt to either of their original holders or to the persons who subsequently acquired the rights to them because under the bill if the CDIC FIRPs a company, then sells some of the assets, pays itself out, solves its problems, it can give back the remainder of the company to the shareholders and the subordinated debt holders. This means the buyers of those subordinated debts or the buyers of those shares can get them in the same fashion as the original holders had them when the company was FIRPed in the first place. It is a very simple amendment.
